  "local_port": 48352,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Videos: What is the file size per hour of recording 720p of video?",
  "response": "The file size of a 720p video recording can vary significantly based on the codec used, the bit rate, and other factors such as the complexity of the scenes being recorded. However, there are general estimates that can help provide a rough idea.\n\nFor 720p resolution, a commonly used bit rate might range from 1,500 kbps to 4,000 kbps (kilobits per second).\n\nTo estimate the file size per hour:\n\n1. **Lower Bit Rate (1,500 kbps)**\n   \\[ \\text{File Size} = \\text{Bit Rate} \\times \\text{Duration} \\]\n\n   \\[ \\text{File Size} = 1,500 \\, \\text{kbps} \\times 3600 \\, \\text{seconds} \\]\n\n   \\[ \\text{File Size} = 5,400,000 \\, \\text{kbits} \\]\n\n   Converting kilobits to megabytes:\n   \n   \\[ \\text{File Size} = \\frac{5,400,000 \\, \\text{kbits}}{8 \\times 1024} \\approx 658 \\, \\text{MB} \\]\n\n2. **Higher Bit Rate (4,000 kbps)**\n   \\[ \\text{File Size} = 4,000 \\, \\text{kbps} \\times 3600 \\, \\text{seconds} \\]\n\n   \\[ \\text{File Size} = 14,400,000 \\, \\text{kbits} \\]\n\n   Converting kilobits to megabytes:\n   \n   \\[ \\text{File Size} = \\frac{14,400,000 \\, \\text{kbits}}{8 \\times 1024} \\approx 1,757 \\, \\text{MB} \\]\n\nSo, the file size per hour of recording 720p video typically ranges from approximately **658 MB to 1,757 MB** depending on the bit rate and other factors.",
